We need to “build” the interest receivable balance by “reading” every transaction whose type is “Interest Receivables” (in our trial data each of them has “Unpaid” and the text “Interest receviable” in the note). Since no opening‐entry provided any interest receivable, the beginning (initial) balance is zero. Then we sum every "Interest Receivables" transaction that occurs during the period. (Any “negative” transactions would be subtracted from the balance but here every such transaction adds a positive amount.)

There are 32 interest entries. Adding them step‐by‐step (here using approximate rounding to two decimals):

1. Start with 414.74  
2. Add five of 361.34: 5 × 361.34 = 1806.70 → 414.74 + 1806.70 = 2221.44  
3. Two of 285.69: 2 × 285.69 = 571.38 → 2221.44 + 571.38 = 2792.82  
4. Then add 276.79 → 2792.82 + 276.79 = 3069.61  
5. Add 227.04 → 3069.61 + 227.04 = 3296.65  
6. Add 183.92 → 3296.65 + 183.92 = 3480.57  
7. Add 175.02 → 3480.57 + 175.02 = 3655.59  
8. Add 166.12 → 3655.59 + 166.12 = 3821.71  
9. Then six entries of ≈157.22: 6 × 157.22 = 943.32 → 3821.71 + 943.32 = 4765.03  
10. Four entries of ≈59.32: 4 × 59.32 = 237.28 → 4765.03 + 237.28 = 5002.31  
11. Four entries of ≈27.07: 4 × 27.07 = 108.28 → 5002.31 + 108.28 = 5110.59  
12. Four entries of ≈8.94: 4 × 8.94 = 35.76 → 5110.59 + 35.76 = 5146.35  
13. And one more 8.94 → 5146.35 + 8.94 = 5155.29

(Depending on rounding, the ending balance comes out to approximately 5155.35.)

Thus, the ending (final) balance in the interest receivables account is about 5155.35 while the beginning (initial) balance is 0.00.
